The problem is with the first argument to the `set` method. It expects an instance of the object that you&#39;re trying to modify to perform the change on. Right now, what you&#39;re doing is similar to trying to execute `null.logFile = newValue`, which obviously will fail.

You need to add another argument to your `setFinal` method, and pass the `logger` variable to it to use as that parameter.

    public static void main(String[] args) throws NoSuchFieldException, SecurityException, Exception {

      MyLogger logger = new MyLogger();
      System.out.println(logger.getLogFile());

      setFinal(MyLogger.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;logFile&quot;), logger, new File(&quot;changed&quot;));
      System.out.println(logger.getLogFile());
    }

    private static void setFinal(Field field, Object toModify, Object newValue) throws Exception {
      field.setAccessible(true);

      Field modifiersField = Field.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;modifiers&quot;);
      modifiersField.setAccessible(true);
      modifiersField.setInt(field, field.getModifiers() &amp; ~Modifier.FINAL);

      field.set(toModify, newValue);
    }

You are using the `Field.set` method in the wrong way. You need to supply the ***object*** on which the new field value has to be set, in your code it should be the `logger` object but you are passing `null`:

    public static void main(String[] args) throws NoSuchFieldException, SecurityException, Exception {

        MyLogger logger = new MyLogger();
        System.out.println(logger.getLogFile());

        setFinal(logger, MyLogger.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;logFile&quot;), new File(&quot;changed&quot;));
        System.out.println(logger.getLogFile());
    }

    private static void setFinal(MyLogger logger, Field field, Object newValue) throws Exception {
        field.setAccessible(true);

        Field modifiersField = Field.class.getDeclaredField(&quot;modifiers&quot;);
        modifiersField.setAccessible(true);
        modifiersField.setInt(field, field.getModifiers() &amp; ~Modifier.FINAL);

        field.set(logger, newValue);
    }
This is as per the method signature of `Field.set` from the [docs](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/reflect/Field.html#set(java.lang.Object,%20java.lang.Object)):


&gt; Sets the field represented by this Field object on the specified
&gt; object argument to the specified new value.

I am able to do it like this using java.lang.reflect.Method check the below code whether it helps to fix your issue.    

    Method method = MyLogger.getClass().getDeclaredMethod(&quot;getLogFile&quot;);
        		method.setAccessible(true);
in getDeclaredMethod you need to give full method name.

